Elsje Du Toit, Netwerk24 (iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Richard's Bay - A Free State boy who fell out of a tree over the long weekend and had to spend a few days in high care, is in a stable condition.John Jackson, 8, a Grade 3 pupil at Wilgerivier school in Frankfort, still has a headache and is complaining of nausea, his dad, Reverend John Jackson, told Netwerk24.&ldquo;He&rsquo;s been transferred to the children's ward, but he&rsquo;s not quite himself yet,&rdquo; said Jackson snr. &ldquo;He&rsquo;s talking, but he&rsquo;s keeping it to a minimum.&rdquo; The Jacksons were on their way to St Lucia for the long weekend when they stopped in Pongola on Friday. John climbed a tree and fell about three metres onto a cement slab, hitting his head and back. Jackson, a minister at the NG Church at Frankfort, in the Free State, said his son was unconscious after the fall.&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;Like any other young boy, he loves climbing trees. After the fall, he was out cold,&rdquo; he said. His mother, Dr Helena Jackson, performed mouth-to-mouth resuscitation. &ldquo;Then we got him to a local doctor as fast as possible.&rdquo; John jnr was stabilised there and taken by ambulance to the Netcare The Bay Hospital in Richards Bay, where he was admitted to the high care unit. &ldquo;He&rsquo;s doing well, but is not really eating because of the nausea. He also was in a lot of pain on Sunday.&rdquo;Jackson said they&rsquo;d be staying in Richards Bay until John jnr was well enough to travel.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.